main event: Two unidentified aerial objects were observed at the Mt. Palomar Observatory in California on September 26, 1950, by two Air Force officers who were initially observing the movement of celestial bodies.
interesting points: The objects were observed moving at a great speed horizontally, from approximately 310° to 100°, emitting a bluish-white light intermittently, with no exhaust trail observed.
The witnesses reported the sound of the objects as a swishing, loud noise similar to rocket exhaust, indicating a possible propulsion system.
The size of the objects appeared to be that of a star or a third constellation, and their shape was described as indefinite.
No photographs or sketches of the observed objects were available, limiting the visual documentation of the sighting.
The report was downgraded at 3-year intervals and declassified after 12 years, suggesting a lack of conclusive explanation for the observed phenomena.
photographs: no photographs available in the report
